nonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Chacombe was born in 1175, in Chacombe, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Hugh de Chaucombe, was 26 and his mother, Hodienne De LUCERNE, was 25. He had at least 2 daughters with Juliane de Cornhill. He died in 1213, in his hometown, at the age of 38, and was buried in Chacombe Priory, Chacombe, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1175–1213":"1175–1213","1170–1261":"1170–1261","1206–1271":"1206–1271","1210–1278":"1210–1278","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1150–1215":"1150–1215","1175":"1175","1174":"1174","1261":"1261","1150":"1150","1271":"1271","1170":"1170","1206":"1206","1206?":"1206","1215":"1215","1149":"1149","1213":"1213","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1210":"umbes 1210","Chacombe Priory, Chacombe, Northamptonshire, England":"Chacombe Priory, Chacombe, Northamptonshire, England","Banbury, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chacombe, Northamptonshire, England":"Chacombe, Northamptonshire, England","Chaucombe, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1175–1213":"1175–1213","1170–1261":"1170–1261","1206–1271":"1206–1271","1210–1278":"1210–1278","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1150–1215":"1150–1215","1175":"1175","1174":"1174","1261